  "prompt": "Why do American writers use yellow paper?",
  "response": "American writers may choose to use yellow paper for a few reasons, but it's not universally common. Here are some possible motivations:\n\n1. **Reduced Eye Strain**: Yellow paper can be easier on the eyes compared to standard white paper. The softer color may reduce glare from lighting, making it more comfortable for long writing sessions.\n\n2. **Aesthetic Appeal**: Some writers might prefer the look of yellow paper or find it more visually appealing. It can create a different mood or atmosphere that aligns with their creative process.\n\n3. **Creativity and Inspiration**: Certain colors, including yellow, can stimulate creativity and inspiration. A change in paper color might encourage a writer to think differently or feel more motivated.\n\n4. **Personal Preference**: Simply put, individual preferences can lead writers to use yellow paper. Some may have nostalgic feelings associated with it or simply like the way their notes or drafts look on yellow paper.\n\n5. **Tradition**: In some cases, the use of yellow paper may be a part of a personal or cultural tradition among certain groups or types of writers.\n\nOverall, while yellow paper isn't universally embraced by all American writers, those who do use it have their unique reasons for doing so.",
